<h2>11.1 Looking things up by name</h2>
<p>A list finds things by position (index 0, 1, 2...); a dictionary finds things by name: <code>prices = {"potion": 5, "sword": 20}</code> lets you ask <code>prices["sword"]</code> and get <code>20</code> straight back, no counting needed – exactly how a shop's price list works.</p>
<p><strong>Worked example:</strong> <code>cart = ["sword", "potion", "potion"]</code> with <code>prices = {"sword": 20, "potion": 5}</code>: total_cost loops through the cart one item at a time – sword looks up to 20, the first potion looks up to 5, the second potion looks up to 5 again – and sums them: 20 + 5 + 5 = 30 coins total, even though "potion" only appears once as a KEY in the dictionary.</p>

